Part III: Eigenfaces and Simple Face Recognition [15 Points]¶

In this project, we will apply a simplified illustration of using PCA for face recognition. We will use a subset of data from the famous Yale Face dataset. First, given a set of images for each person, we generate the eigenface using these images. We will treat one picture from the same person as one data point for that person. Note that we will first vectorize each image, which was originally a matrix. Thus, the data matrix (for each person) is a matrix; each row is a vectorized picture. We will find weight vectors to combine the pictures to extract different eigenfaces that correspond to that person's pictures' first few principal components.

Prior to beginning our analysis, we first need to do load in both our libraries and our image data.

    return np.array(image.convert ('L'))

    return Image.fromarray(image_np.astype(np.uint8), mode='L')

    if ax is None:
        f = plt.figure()
        ax = plt.axes()
    ax.imshow(im,
              interpolation='nearest',

Now that our images have been correctly loaded for both subjects, we will begin the process of extracting the eigen faces. First, we apply centering to both subjects' image arrays. After this, we apply singular value decomposition via NumPy which equivalent to applying PCA. We then retrieve the top six principal components from both subjects resulting embeddings. In the cells below, we implement principal components analysis on the Yale faces dataset and return the top 6 "eigenfaces" for each of the two subjects with two images utilized as held out data.

In [22]:
subject_1_centered = subject_1_array - np.expand_dims(np.average(subject_1_array,axis=1),axis=1)
subject_2_centered = subject_2_array - np.expand_dims(np.average(subject_2_array,axis=1),axis=1)

U_s1,Sigma_s1,VT_s1 = np.linalg.svd(np.cov(subject_1_centered,ddof=0))
U_s2,Sigma_s2,VT_s2 = np.linalg.svd(np.cov(subject_2_centered,ddof=0))
VT_s1_k = VT_s1[0:6,:]
VT_s2_k = VT_s2[0:6,:]
Sigma_s1_k = Sigma_s1[0:6]
Sigma_s2_k = Sigma_s2[0:6]
subject_1_pc = []
subject_2_pc = []
for i in range(0,6):
    subject_1_pc.append(np.reshape(VT_s1_k[i,:].T.dot(subject_1_centered) / np.sqrt(Sigma_s1_k[i]),(243,320)))
    subject_2_pc.append(np.reshape(VT_s2_k[i,:].T.dot(subject_2_centered) / np.sqrt(Sigma_s2_k[i]),(243,320)))

As we can see from the output above, subject 1's "eigenfaces" certainly show some interesting behavior. In eigenface 0 we can see that PCA took strong cues from the subject's hair, eyes, chin, and mouth. In the second eigenface for subject 1, we can see what appears to be a shadow to the right side of the subject with the left illuminated. This is an especially interesting result given that the input dataset contained 2 images with lighting coming from either side. This eigenface could very well be PCA's accusation for such a difference in features. The remaining eigenfaces of subject one has much less clear features identifiable, which can be seen from the low contrast and color intensity of the images. However, in each of them we do see small highlights of facial features like the nose in eigenface 4, the cheekbones in eigenface 3, or chin and eyebrows of eigenface 5. Collectively I was very impressed with PCA's ability to derive some sort of features to the images. However, I still have my doubts as to whether they will prove useful in facial recognition tasks.

In evaluating the eigenfaces generated form the training images of subject 2, it is notable to point out that we had a smaller dataset than subject 1 by a single image. As we can see from the eigenface 0 of subject 2, there is a striking contrasted generated between the figure and their surroundings. This behavior is very similar to that noted within the analysis of eigenface 0 of subject 1. As was the case with subject 1, eigenface 0 in subject 2 seems to place higher weights on the hair and eye features of the individual. It is notable however that subject 2 did not receive the highlighting of the chin area as subject 1 did. Again, when moving onto subject 2's eigenface 1, we see a distinct shadow pattern. This shadow pattern seems to persist in subject 2 more than subject 1. Collectively, we reach many of the same conclusions about subject 2 as we did with subject one which could spell trouble for a task that requires classification between two differing faces, but the algorithm was also not applied for such as task in this implementation to begin with. A closing note on this is also to note the immense importance eigenface 0 will always have over all subsequent eigenfaces as this is the projection that by far maximizes variance the most this can be demonstrated through basic examination of a sorted eigenvector plot.

Now we will perform a simple face recognition task. Face recognition through PCA is proceeded as follows. Given the test image $\textsf{subject01-test.gif}$ and $\textsf{subject02-test.gif}$, first downsize by a factor of 4 (as before), and vectorize each image. Take the top eigenfaces of Subject 1 and Subject 2, respectively. Then we calculate the normalized inner product score of the 2 vectorized test images with the vectorized eigenfaces:

$$s_{ij} =\frac{\textsf{(eigenface})_i^T \textsf{(test image)}_j}{\|\textsf{(eigenface}_i)\| \cdot\|\textsf{(test image)}_j\|}$$

By taking the top two eigenfaces from each subject in the analysis above, we can test their performance by measuring their similarity to our held-out test images for each of the two subjects. The above formula which we will use to calculate this level of similarity is also or equivalently called the Cosine similarity function. By applying this function for each of our respective four cases we will receive a value between -1 and 1 for each case. In this scale, a value that approaches -1 is said to be increasingly dissimilar, and alternatively a value that approaches 1 is said to be increasingly similar with respect to the inputs. In this scale it is also notable to point out that a value of 0 would be the middle ground indicating neither similarity nor dissimilarity. Below is the output for each of the above cases represented in matrix form $S_{ij}$ as specified above having rows represented by eigenfaces for subject 1 and two and columns representing subjects 1 and 2 respectively. Thus, the matrix output (0,0) should tell us with what level of similarity subject 1's test image had to the eigenfaces constructed for subject 1, and entry (1,0) demonstrating the level of similarity the eigenfaces constructed for subject 2 had on the test image for subject 1. In this construction, we will want to see (in a good facial recognition algorithm) on diagonal elements very close to 1 as these elements would indicate correct matches. Elements lying in the off-diagonal space would ideally have values close to negative one indicating strong dissimilarity to non-matching subjects. However, as our output will show this method of facial recognition leaves much to be desired in the aspect of accuracy.

As we can see from the output above, our eigenfaces did not do the best of job in identifying the input test faces. In three of the four cases, it found the two representations to be moderately dissimilar, and one case where it was found slightly negative but generally neither similar nor dissimilar. Untimely, if we wanted to deploy such an implementation for facial recognition this model would prove to be quite poor under either subject or for either eigenface. Going forward there are many areas we could work to improve the model. Firstly, we did some initial down sampling on the images which could have impacted the results depending on the exact method of down sampling used. Secondly, we could attempt to employing some additional de-nosing techniques to prevent background variations from playing a part in the projections. Finally, we could employ non-linear reduction methods like IsoMap to the data and see if it would better capture some of the data variation within its embeddings. I suspect that Isomaps ability to separate facial directions could play a significant role in correct facial identification in application such as phones where a face will not be perfectly square to the camera. All of these are methods that could be explored in furthering the capabilities of such a facial recognition model.
